{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17619804","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17619804"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:36:17+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:36:17+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16580"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16580","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16580"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9271"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75726"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9271","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9271"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16580"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61244"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"32"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"3310"},{"type":"tags","id":"4930"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5882"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"21962"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21967"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75726","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75726"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old man presents to the emergency department following an assault. He has a Glasgow Coma Scale score of 14 (confused) and a large contusion over his right temporal region. A computed tomography (CT) scan of the head is performed.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the typical appearance of a cerebral contusion on CT imaging?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Crescentic hyperdense collection adjacent to skull","Mixed density areas of haemorrhage and oedema","Uniform hypodense region with sharp margins","Homogeneous hyperdense collection with mass effect","Isodense lesion with surrounding vasogenic oedema"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECerebral contusions are traumatic brain injuries that occur when the brain tissue impacts against the inner surface of the skull. They are characterised by areas of focal brain injury with associated bleeding and oedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMixed density areas of haemorrhage and oedema\u003C/strong\u003E is the classic appearance of a cerebral contusion on CT. The hyperdense areas represent acute haemorrhage, while hypodense areas represent oedema and tissue damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ehomogeneous hyperdense collection with mass effect\u003C/strong\u003E is more typical of an acute subdural or epidural haematoma, where there is pure blood collection without underlying brain tissue damage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Euniform hypodense region with sharp margins\u003C/strong\u003E would be more consistent with cerebral infarction or established oedema, rather than an acute traumatic injury.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eisodense lesion with surrounding vasogenic oedema\u003C/strong\u003E would be more typical of a subacute to chronic subdural haematoma, where the blood products have begun to break down.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ecrescentic hyperdense collection adjacent to skull\u003C/strong\u003E is the classic appearance of an epidural haematoma, which forms between the skull and dura mater, typically associated with arterial bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EContusions commonly occur at sites of direct impact (coup injury) and at sites opposite to the impact (contrecoup injury). They are particularly common in areas where the brain contacts rough bone surfaces, such as the frontal and temporal poles. Important management principles include close neurological observation, as contusions can expand over 24-48 hours, and repeat imaging if there is clinical deterioration.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Cerebral contusions appear as mixed density lesions on CT with areas of haemorrhage (hyperdense) and oedema (hypodense).","Contusions commonly occur at sites of impact and where the brain contacts rough surfaces of the skull base.","Cerebral contusions can expand over 24-48 hours, requiring close observation and repeat imaging if deterioration occurs."],"references":["Adatia K, Newcombe VFJ, Menon DK. Contusion Progression Following Traumatic Brain Injury: A Review of Clinical and Radiological Predictors, and Influence on Outcome. Neurocrit Care. 2021 Feb;34(1):312-324. doi: 10.1007/s12028-020-00994-4. PMID: 32462411; PMCID: PMC7253145.","Alahmadi H, Vachhrajani S, Cusimano MD. The natural history of brain contusion: an analysis of radiological and clinical progression. J Neurosurg. 2010 May;112(5):1139-45. doi: 10.3171/2009.5.JNS081369. PMID: 19575576.","Pellot JE, De Jesus O. Cerebral Contusion. 2023 Aug 28. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32965818.","Jirlow U, Hossain I, Korhonen O, Depreitere B, Rostami E. Cerebral contusions - Pathomechanism, predictive factors for progression and historical and current management. Brain Spine. 2024 Aug 28;4:103329. doi: 10.1016/j.bas.2024.103329. PMID: 39281852; PMCID: PMC11402187."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61244"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16580"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61244","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61244"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-30T20:34:09+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-30T20:35:01+10:30"},"relati